# Controllers

Controllers must be **lightweight**. They may only:

1. Read `req` (params, body, `req.user` from auth middleware)
2. Call a **service** (or temporarily model only when migrating — prefer services for new code)
3. Return `res.json(...)` with `{ success: true, data }` or pass errors via `next(err)`

## Forbidden in controllers

- Complex queries, matching algorithms, or multi-step workflows
- Duplicated formatting/business rules (move to `services/` or `utils/`)
- Direct Socket.io business logic beyond delegating to a service

## Good vs bad

```javascript
// BAD — business logic in controller
exports.register = async (req, res) => {
  const existing = await User.findOne({ email: req.body.email });
  if (existing) return res.status(400).json({ success: false, error: "..." });
  const user = await User.create({ ... });
  // ...hashing, token logic, formatting...
};

// GOOD — delegate to service
exports.register = async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    const result = await authService.register(req.body);
    res.status(201).json({ success: true, data: result });
  } catch (err) {
    next(err);
  }
};
```

Use `next(err)` instead of ad-hoc try/catch in every method when centralized error middleware handles it.
